lates ARB/USDT funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC using a time-weighted average of the premium/discount to spot prices. Long positions pay funding when rates are positive, while shorts pay when negative. The exchange's zero maker fee structure allows traders to establish positions without additional trading costs beyond the 0.03% taker fee. MEXC's funding rate cap typically ranges from -0.75% to +0.75% per interval to prevent extreme rate manipulation."}]]}],"$L3",["$L4","$L5","$L6"],"$L7"]}],"$L8"]}]]}],["$L9","$La"],"$Lb"]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
3:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ARB","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ARB represents Arbitrum's native governance token, offering significant funding rate volatility due to Layer 2 ecosystem speculation and DeFi activity flows. MEXC's early listing of ARB and zero maker fees create advantageous conditions for funding rate arbitrage compared to other exchanges. The pair's large volume classification indicates sufficient liquidity for meaningful position sizes in funding strategies."}]]}]
4:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ARB/USDT funding rates on MEXC have shown distinct patterns correlating with Arbitrum ecosystem developments and broader DeFi trends. Positive funding dominates during periods of ARB staking announcements or major DApp launches on Arbitrum, often reaching 0.2-0.4% per 8-hour interval. Negative funding frequently occurs during broader crypto market corrections when leveraged longs are liquidated. The token's governance utility creates additional volatility around proposal voting periods, generating funding arbitrage opportunities for traders monitoring Arbitrum governance calendars."}]]}]
5:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fees create significant advantages for ARB funding arbitrage versus exchanges charging 0.02-0.05% maker fees on similar positions. Cross-exchange arbitrage opportunities frequently emerge between MEXC and Binance or Bybit during high volatility periods, with funding rate differentials of 0.1-0.3% per interval. Delta-neutral strategies combining MEXC ARB perps with spot ARB holdings can capture funding payments while maintaining market exposure neutrality. The 8-hour interval alignment with major exchanges facilitates synchronized funding collection across multiple venues for enhanced returns."}]]}]
6:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's thinner order books for ARB/USDT create elevated slippage risks during rapid market movements, particularly affecting larger position sizes above $50,000 notional. The exchange's questionable volume reporting practices require additional due diligence on actual liquidity depths before deploying significant capital. Funding rate arbitrage positions face overnight gap risks during major Arbitrum ecosystem announcements or broader Layer 2 narrative shifts. MEXC's limited regulatory compliance compared to Tier 1 exchanges introduces counterparty risks that must be weighed against the zero maker fee advantages in funding strategies."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lc",null,{"items":[{"question":"What are the funding interval times for ARB/USDT on MEXC?","answer":"MEXC charges funding for ARB/USDT every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC. Positions held during these times will pay or receive funding based on the calculated rate and position direction."},{"question":"How do MEXC's zero maker fees affect ARB funding arbitrage profitability?","answer":"Zero maker fees allow traders to establish ARB positions without trading costs when using limit orders, significantly improving funding arbitrage net returns. This advantage is particularly valuable for frequent position adjustments and cross-exchange arbitrage strategies where trading costs would otherwise erode funding profits."},{"question":"What position sizes work best for ARB funding strategies on MEXC?","answer":"MEXC's ARB/USDT order book typically supports positions up to $25,000-$50,000 without significant slippage impact. Larger positions should be split across multiple entries or combined with other exchanges to maintain execution efficiency and avoid moving the market against the intended funding capture."},{"question":"How volatile are ARB funding rates compared to other Layer 2 tokens on MEXC?","answer":"ARB funding rates show moderate to high volatility, typically ranging from -0.2% to +0.4% per 8-hour interval during normal market conditions. This volatility level is comparable to other Layer 2 governance tokens but generally higher than established assets like BTC or ETH, creating more frequent arbitrage opportunities."}]}]
